Now I have enough context to perform a thorough code review. Let me analyze the changes:

# Change summary: This commit adds Vercel deployment configuration, RSS feed generation, community themes marketplace, webring widget, live component previews, CSS-only search functionality, dark mode support, and various accessibility improvements to the Shallot website.

## File: shallot_website/src/showcase.rs
### L251: [MEDIUM] Missing component imports may cause runtime panics.

The `render_preview` function matches on component names and renders them, but only 8 components are actually imported at the top of the file (lines 9-18). If any other component name is matched, it falls through to the placeholder. However, the `SAMPLE_COMPONENTS` array contains 129 components, and only 8 will render actual previews.

This creates an inconsistent user experience where most component cards show "Live preview" placeholders instead of actual renders.

Suggested change:
```rust
// Either import all components that should have live previews:
use shallot_components::{
    alert::{Alert, AlertKind},
    avatar::Avatar,
    badge::Badge,
    border_beam::BorderBeam,
    button::Button,
    card::Card,
    confetti::Confetti,
    input::Input,
    skeleton::Skeleton,
    // Add more components as needed for live previews
};

// OR limit the match statement to only imported components
fn render_preview(name: &str) -> Markup {
    match name {
        "Button" => { /* ... */ }
        "Badge" => { /* ... */ }
        // ... only for actually imported components
        _ => html! {
            div class="sh-component-card__placeholder" {
                span { "Live preview" }
            }
        },
    }
}
```

### L424: [LOW] Hardcoded GitHub URL should be centralized.

The download button href uses a hardcoded placeholder URL. This is repeated for every component card and should use a constant or environment variable.

Suggested change:
```rust
// Add a constant at the top of the file
const GITHUB_REPO_URL: &str = "https://github.com/shallot-rs/shallot";

// Then use it in the download link
a
    href=(format!("data:text/plain;charset=utf-8,{}example%20code%20for%20{}", "%5B%20Example%20code%20%5D", name.to_lowercase()))
    download=(format!("{}_example.rs", name.to_lowercase()))
    class="sh-code-download"
{
    span aria-hidden="true" { "📥" }
    " Download"
}
```

## File: shallot_website/src/theme_switcher.rs
### L133: [MEDIUM] Dark mode checkbox lacks proper implementation.

The dark mode checkbox is added at line 133 with `id="option-dark-mode"`, but the CSS selector at line 407 uses `#option-dark-mode:checked ~ html` which won't work because:
1. The `html` element is not a sibling of the checkbox
2. The checkbox is inside `.sh-theme-switcher`, not at the document root

The dark mode toggle will not function as intended.

Suggested change:
```rust
// Option 1: Use data attribute with JavaScript alternative (but violates zero-JS)
// Option 2: Use CSS :has() on a parent element that wraps html
// Option 3: Use URL hash approach for persistence

// For a pure CSS solution, wrap the entire body content:
html:has(#option-dark-mode:checked) {
    --sh-text: #f9fafb;
    --sh-text-secondary: #d1d5db;
    // ... other dark mode variables
}

// Or use the existing data-theme approach from lib.rs:
// Add an onchange handler to set data-theme attribute
// (but this requires JS, so consider removing dark mode toggle)
```

### L377-L409: [LOW] New theme presets use incorrect selector indices.

The new themes "Dark Ocean", "Dark Forest", and "Dark Sunset" are added to `THEME_PRESETS` array (lines 58-80), making them indices 7, 8, and 9. However, the CSS selectors reference `#theme-7`, `#theme-8`, `#theme-9` which assumes these are the correct radio button IDs.

If the radio buttons are generated dynamically, ensure the loop index matches. If manually created, verify the IDs match.

## File: shallot_website/src/lib.rs
### L89-L93: [LOW] Hardcoded external links should be constants.

The footer contains hardcoded GitHub URL that should be centralized for maintainability.

Suggested change:
```rust
// Add a constant
const GITHUB_REPO_URL: &str = "https://github.com/shallot-rs/shallot";

// Use it in the template
a href=(GITHUB_REPO_URL) { "💾 GitHub" }
```

### L105: [MEDIUM] Missing `components.css` file reference.

Line 68 references `link rel="stylesheet" href="styles/components.css";` but the `main.rs` file doesn't generate this file. This will result in a 404 error when the website loads.

Suggested change:
```rust
// In main.rs, add the missing CSS generation:
fs::write(styles_dir.join("components.css"), component_docs::component_docs_css())
    .expect("Failed to write components.css");

// Or remove the link if not needed
```

## File: shallot_website/src/main.rs
### L19: [MEDIUM] Missing CSS file generation for `components.css`.

The main.rs file generates `main.css`, `retro.css`, and `showcase.css`, but not `components.css` which is referenced in `lib.rs` line 68. This will cause a broken stylesheet link.

Suggested change:
```rust
// Add the missing CSS generation
use shallot_website::component_docs_css; // Import if it exists

// In main():
fs::write(styles_dir.join("components.css"), component_docs_css())
    .expect("Failed to write components.css");

// Or if components.css is not needed, remove the link from lib.rs
```

## File: shallot_website/src/rss.rs
### L48: [LOW] Hardcoded URLs should use constants.

The RSS feed contains hardcoded URLs that should be centralized.

Suggested change:
```rust
const BASE_URL: &str = "https://shallot.rs";

// Then use it:
link href=(BASE_URL) rel="alternate";
link href=(format!("{}/feed.xml", BASE_URL)) rel="self";
```

### L53: [LOW] Static timestamp should be dynamic.

The `updated` timestamp is hardcoded to `"2026-02-24T00:00:00Z"`. For a production RSS feed, this should reflect the actual latest update time.

---

**Note:** The review focuses on the Rust code changes. The documentation files (`CODE_REVIEW.md`, `INFRASTRUCTURE_IMPROVEMENTS.md`, `README.md`) and configuration files (`.vercel/`, `vercel.json`) were reviewed but contain no functional code issues - they are informational and configuration-only.

